races.nyt_race_description: Senator Kelly Loeffler, who was appointed to her seat in 2019 and is seeking to finish a term that ends in 2022, is vying against the Rev. Raphael Warnock, who leads Ebenezer Baptist Church in Atlanta. In November’s crowded special election, Mr. Warnock finished with 32.9 percent of the vote and Ms. Loeffler had 25.9 percent.

live_update.author: Nate Cohn
live_update.text: Democrats are starting to pull clearly, if slightly, ahead in our estimates, as they're outperforming our expectations across all vote methods. The only good news for the GOP is that the election day turnout is a hair higher than we expected. Republican hopes rest on the election day vote; there's still a lot of it left, and maybe they'll do better with what's left than what's counted. With the race so close, they'd have to do only a little bit better than they've done so far to fight back to a dead heat.

races.nyt_race_description: David Perdue, a Republican whose Senate term ended on Sunday, has faced a competitive challenge from Jon Ossoff, a documentary film executive. In November, Mr. Perdue fell just short of the majority he would have needed to avoid a runoff, winning 49.7 percent of the vote, while Mr. Ossoff had 47.9 percent — a difference of about 88,000 votes.

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: Kelly Loeffler is only the second woman to serve as a senator from Georgia. The other, Rebecca Latimer Felton, served for one day in 1922.

liveUpdates.author: Mike Baker
liveUpdates.text: 40 percent of the estimated ballots have been counted. Democrats hold leads, but there are a lot of remaining votes, especially in Republican strongholds in northern Georgia.

liveUpdates.author: Trip Gabriel
liveUpdates.text: TargetSmart, a Democratic data firm, estimates Democrats improved on their share of early votes by 2.8 points compared to November. Election day turnout could erase that advantage.

liveUpdates.author: Jim Rutenberg
liveUpdates.text: Fair Fight Action, founded by Stacey Abrams, is urging voters to stay in line — a reminder of Georgia’s history of voter suppression, and a sign of the down-to-the-wire races.

liveUpdates.author: Jennifer Medina
liveUpdates.text: Another sign of the importance of the race — and the money poured into it: 40 percent of voters surveyed by The A.P. said they were contacted on behalf of both parties’ candidates.

liveUpdates.author: Trip Gabriel
liveUpdates.text: In the first post-November election without Trump on the ballot, some analyses of early voting suggest Democrats maintained their enthusiasm, especially thanks to Black voters.

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: Polls of voters conducted by The A.P. reveal that David Perdue has slightly higher favorability ratings than his fellow Republican Kelly Loeffler — 50 percent to 47 percent.

liveUpdates.author: Jeremy Peters
liveUpdates.text: All that advertising seems to have worked for Republicans in at least one way: According to A.P. surveys, more voters see Ossoff and Warnock as “extreme” than Perdue or Loeffler.

liveUpdates.author: Matt Flegenheimer
liveUpdates.text: Text from a progressive strategist involved in Democratic efforts in Georgia: “Ugh. Here we go. That feeling I hate is back: hope.”

liveUpdates.author: Adam Nagourney
liveUpdates.text: There’s big support among Georgia voters (74 percent) for requiring people to wear masks when around people outside the home, according to A.P. voter surveys.

liveUpdates.author: Nate Cohn
liveUpdates.text: Needle update: Democrats are faring a hair better than expected in the absentee vote, but the big question mark is the election day vote and we still have very little of it.

liveUpdates.author: Jim Rutenberg
liveUpdates.text: The Trump-style, anti-press movement is alive and well in Georgia tonight: Georgia Public Broadcasting says the state G.O.P. barred a reporter from its election-night headquarters.

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: There’s also a race for Public Service Commission, which sets utility rates. Lauren “Bubba” McDonald, 82, an ardent Trump supporter, is facing a challenge by Daniel Blackman, 41.

liveUpdates.author: Mike Baker
liveUpdates.text: We are now at nearly 400,000 votes counted, and thus far the clearest takeaway is that both races are really too close to call.

liveUpdates.author: Danny Hakim
liveUpdates.text: Nearly $300 million was spent on advertising in the Loeffler-Warnock race, making it the second most expensive Senate race ever — behind only Perdue-Ossoff.

liveUpdates.author: Danny Hakim
liveUpdates.text: Roughly $404 million was spent on advertising in the Perdue-Ossoff race, according to Advertising Analytics, making it the most expensive Senate race ever.

liveUpdates.author: Matt Flegenheimer
liveUpdates.text: A.P. surveys get at the dissonance of the G.O.P. message: Most voters say Senate control is important, but if you believe Trump’s false claims that he won, the Senate isn’t up for grabs.

liveUpdates.author: Jennifer Medina
liveUpdates.text: Most Georgia voters said that deciding which party controls the Senate was the “single most important factor” in casting their ballot, according to A.P. voter surveys.

liveUpdates.author: Jim Rutenberg
liveUpdates.text: A.P. voter surveys show that Secretary of State Brad Raffensperger has weathered Trump’s savage attacks: 57 percent said they approved of the way he handled the 2020 results.

liveUpdates.author: Matt Flegenheimer
liveUpdates.text: Republicans say electing GA Dems would put the far left in charge. In reality, a 50-50 Senate would make people like Joe Manchin of WV, the most conservative Senate Dem, very powerful.

liveUpdates.author: Lisa Lerer
liveUpdates.text: Officials were able to process and organize, but not count, early votes before 7 p.m. They hope that rule change will speed up counting of the 3.1 million early ballots cast.

liveUpdates.author: Maggie Astor
liveUpdates.text: Most polls are closed after what officials said was a mostly smooth day of voting in Georgia, but a handful of precincts will stay open past 7 p.m. because of earlier problems.

liveUpdates.author: Shaila Dewan
liveUpdates.text: I first interviewed Stacey Abrams around 2011, when she became minority leader of the Georgia Assembly. She told me then that Georgia could turn blue if Democrats would invest.

liveUpdates.author: Mike Baker
liveUpdates.text: 61 percent of voters surveyed in Georgia report that they believe Joe Biden was legitimately elected president, according to new A.P. survey results.

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: New A.P. voter surveys in Georgia show that 32 percent of those voting identify as African-American or Black, a number that indicates high turnout in that demographic group.

liveUpdates.author: Mike Baker
liveUpdates.text: New A.P. voter surveys in Georgia: 59 percent of voters say they are “very” or “somewhat” confident that ineligible votes were not allowed during the presidential election.

liveUpdates.author: Trip Gabriel
liveUpdates.text: Kelly Loeffler was appointed by Georgia’s governor to the Senate in 2019. Another appointed senator, Martha McSally of Arizona, lost in November when she had to face voters.

liveUpdates.author: Mike Baker
liveUpdates.text: You may be wondering why Georgia has these unusual runoff elections. The decades-old system has racist roots — part of an effort to dilute Black voting power.

liveUpdates.author: Lisa Lerer
liveUpdates.text: Expect early returns to show a G.O.P. edge, with conservative counties likely to report results faster. Democratic counties, including suburban Atlanta, typically take more time.

liveUpdates.author: Lisa Lerer
liveUpdates.text: Expect a G.O.P. advantage in the votes reported first. Republicans tend to cast more ballots on election day, which are reported faster than absentee and in-person early votes.
liveUpdates.image_credit: Lynsey Weatherspoon for The New York Times

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: In this campaign, David Perdue has downplayed his extensive dealings in outsourcing manufacturing to China during his career in the apparel and textile industries.

liveUpdates.author: Danny Hakim
liveUpdates.text: Senator Kelly Loeffler has strong Wall Street ties, starting with her husband, the chairman of the New York Stock Exchange, who directed $21 million to a pro-Loeffler PAC.

liveUpdates.author: Mike Baker
liveUpdates.text: Some trivia about the Rev. Raphael Warnock: He gave his first sermon when he was 11 years old. Here’s a closer look at the candidate and his background.

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: Jon Ossoff has worked in politics, but he has never held public office. Yet he is the best-funded Senate candidate in history, according to our recent profile of him.

liveUpdates.author: Lisa Lerer
liveUpdates.text: About 3.1 million people voted early, and that vote appeared to tilt Democratic. If another million people cast ballots today, Republicans believe they are likely to win.

liveUpdates.author: Lisa Lerer
liveUpdates.text: Early voting returns worried some Republicans, who were not happy with the low turnout in conservative Northwest Georgia. They hope Trump’s rally there motivated supporters.

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: At age 33, Jon Ossoff would be just three years over the minimum age for being a U.S. senator if he is elected in today’s runoff. His opponent, David Perdue, is 71.

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: One thing to note: David Perdue is actually former Senator David Perdue. His term expired and the rest of the new Congress was sworn in on Sunday.

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: The Rev. Raphael Warnock, one of the Democratic candidates, is the senior pastor at Ebenezer Baptist Church in Atlanta, where the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. once preached.

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: Kelly Loeffler, one of the Republicans in today’s runoff, was appointed by Gov. Brian Kemp to replace Johnny Isakson, who retired after his diagnosis with Parkinson’s disease.

liveUpdates.author: Stephanie Saul
liveUpdates.text: If Senator Kelly Loeffler wins today, she will have to run again in two years. She is filling out the unexpired term of Senator Johnny Isakson, who retired.

liveUpdates.author: Jim Rutenberg
liveUpdates.text: Another contest is underway — between reality and fantasy, as Trump seeks to sow doubts about Georgia’s election system. State officials are rebutting his charges in real time.

liveUpdates.author: Lisa Lerer
liveUpdates.text: It’s a political cliché, but this election is all about turnout now. Democrats appeared to get the edge in early voting. Can Republicans capture enough votes on election day?
